{"key":"post-9709229","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9709229</id>\n<content>I'd go with a slightly larger blower.&amp;nbsp; If you calculate for your blower in a perfect world, that one might be fine.&amp;nbsp; However, we live in an imperfect world, and there's going to be resistance in the housing, and more resistance as the airflow turns the corner in the plenum behind the filter, etc.,&amp;nbsp; I'd look for one that delivers around 500 cfm @ .9&quot; - 1&quot; of WC.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Once you get it all put together, you want the stream to bend the flame of a bic lighter over 45 to 90 degrees, but not blow it out.&amp;nbsp; If it blows too hard, you can either get a $50 motor speed controller to slow it down, or simply block off part of the intake air supply to choke it down.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The cancer risk is probably the varnish insulation on the windings or something like that, so don't eat or suck on your blower motor.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I gave some detailed info on hooking up graingers motors to another member a few months ago.&amp;nbsp; Search posts using my name and the terms: white wire, green, black, chassis, and you should find it easily.&amp;nbsp; If in doubt, take it to an electrical, or heating and air conditioning shop and they'll wire it up safely to a cord and plug for you.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9709251</next>\n<prev>9708942</prev>\n<first>9708942</first>\n<last>9711982</last>\n<when>1233382692</when>\n<utime>01/31/09 08:18 AM</utime>\n</post>"}